285","1283":"1283","Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Kinalton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom","Brooksby, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Villiers","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): habitational name from Villiers, the name of several places in France, all named from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’ (see   Villars  ). Compare   Devilliers  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Villars","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Andre, Henri.","French: habitational name from any of various places called Villars, from Late Latin <i>villare</i> ‘(part of an) outlying farm, dependent settlement’, a derivative of Latin <i>villa</i> ‘country house, estate’ (later used of a group of houses forming a settlement)."]}]},{"name":"Matthew","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the name of the Christian evangelist, author of the first gospel in the New Testament. His name is a form of the Hebrew name <i>Mattathia</i>, meaning ‘gift of God’, which is fairly common in the Old Testament, being rendered in the Authorized Version in a number of different forms: <i>Mattan(i)ah</i>, <i>Mattatha(h)</i>, <i>Mattithiah</i>, <i>Mattathias</i>, and so on. In the Authorized Version, the evangelist is regularly referred to as <i>Matthew</i>, while the apostle chosen to replace Judas Iscariot is distinguished as   Matthias .  A related name from the same Hebrew roots, but reversed, is   Jonathan .  Throughout the English-speaking world <i>Matthew</i> has been particularly popular since the 1970s."],"variants":[{"name":"Mathew","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Matthew ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Matthew de Villiers was born about 1283, in Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, William de Villiers, was 30 and his mother, Anyce of Brooksby, was 49. He married Clementia Brokesby in 1310, in Brooksby, Leicestershire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died after 1352, in his hometown."},"et":{"Abt 1283–Aft 1352":"umbes 1283–pärast 1352","1283–1352":"1283–1352","1285–Female":"1285–Surnud","1311–1348":"1311–1348","1255–Male":"1255–Surnud","1236–Female":"1236–Surnud","1348":"1348","Abt 1283":"umbes 1283","1236":"1236","Aft 1352":"pärast 1352","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","Abt. 1311":"umbes 1311","1352":"1352","1285":"1285","1283":"1283","Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Kinalton, Nottinghamshire, England":"Kinoulton, Nottinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Brooksby, Leicestershire, England":"Brooksby, Leicestershire, England"},"fi":{"Abt 1283–Aft 1352":"noin 1283–1352 jälkeen","1283–1352":"1283–1352","1285–Female":"1285–Kuollut","1311–1348":"1311–1348","1255–Male":"1255–Kuollut","1236–Female":"1236–Kuollut","1348":"1348","Abt 1283":"noin 1283","1236":"1236","Aft 1352":"1352 jälkeen","1311":"1311","1310":"1310","1255":"1255","Abt. 1311":"noin 1311","1352":"1352","